<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>International&#174; T 444E Diesel Engine - Model Years Late 1997 to 2003 - Crankcase, Crankshaft, Connecting
        Rods, And Pistons - Connecting Rods, Pistons and Piston Rings - Assembly - New Style Connecting Rod
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc graphiccount="6">
        <title>Assembly - New Style Connecting Rod</title>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To avoid personal injury or possible death, wear safety glasses when installing piston pin
                    retaining rings.
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Make sure the connecting rod and piston are assembled correctly to avoid engine damage. The large
                    chamfer side of the connecting rod must be located next to the crankshaft fillet.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <figure>
            <graphic filename="../figF04/F0409.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"
                     box="yes"/>
            <caption>Proper Assembly of the Piston and Connecting Rod</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Piston Stamped "CAM"' Part Number, (Service Pistons Include Oversize
                    Designation)
                </callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Large Chamfer Side of Connecting Rod</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Connect piston to connecting rod as follows:</para>
            <figure>
                <graphic filename="../figF04/F0410.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px" box="yes"/>
                <caption>Installing the Piston Pin</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Piston</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Piston Pin</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Retaining Rings</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Lubricate the piston pin bore in the connecting rod, piston pin bore, and piston pin
                    with clean engine oil.
                </para>
                <figure>
                    <graphic filename="../figF04/F0411.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Installing Piston Pin Retaining Ring</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Pliers</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Retaining Ring</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The retaining ring has a smooth finish side and a rough finish side. The smooth finish
                            side faces the piston pin.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use pliers to install a piston pin retaining ring at one end of piston pin bore.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Insert the connecting rod into the piston. Make sure the bored holes of the connecting
                    rod and piston are aligned.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Slide piston pin through bored holes, stopping at the previously installed retaining
                    ring.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the second retaining ring.</para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <figure>
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0426.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
            <caption>Piston Ring Locations</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Top compression ring</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Intermediate compression ring</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Oil control ring</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use piston ring expansion pliers to install piston rings onto piston as follows:</para>
            <figure>
                <graphic filename="../figeg8/EG8037.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px" box="yes"/>
                <caption>Installing Rings Onto Piston (Typical)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Piston ring expander tool</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Piston</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Piston ring (top compression shown)</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use the piston ring expansion tool to install the oil control ring into the bottom
                    piston groove.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The intermediate ring is identified by two "OO" marks located on the top surface of the
                            ring. The top ring is identified by one single "O" mark located on the top surface of the
                            ring. Make sure the ring is installed with the identification mark facing up (top of
                            piston).
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure>
                    <graphic filename="../figd04/D0414A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Piston Ring Identification Mark (top ring shown)</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use the piston ring expansion tool to install the intermediate ring into the middle
                    piston groove.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">use the piston ring expansion tool to install the to ring into the top piston groove.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Space ring gaps approximately 120&#176; apart after ring installation.</para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
